manner /ˈmænə/

(manners) 

1. N-SING The manner in which you do something is the way that you do it. 方式 

例： She smiled again in a friendly manner. 她又友好地笑了笑。 

例： I'm a professional and I have to conduct myself in a professional manner. 我是专业人士，必须以专业方式行事。 

2. N-SING Someone's manner is the way in which they behave and talk when they are with other people, for example whether they are polite, confident, or bad-tempered. 举止 

例： His manner was self-assured and brusque. 他的举止自负而且粗鲁。 

3. -mannered COMB in ADJ …的态度 

例： Forrest was normally mild-mannered, affable, and untalkative. 福里斯特通常态度温和，和蔼可亲，不善言辞。 

4. N-PLURAL If someone has good manners , they are polite and observe social customs. If someone has bad manners , they are impolite and do not observe these customs. 礼貌 

例： He dressed well and had impeccable manners. 他穿着得体，举止无可挑剔。 

例： The manners of many doctors were appalling. 许多医生很没礼貌。

